---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import NavHeader from "@/components/NavHeader.astro";
import Footer from "@/components/Footer.astro";

const codeHF = `const repoId = "google/gemma-3-4b-it";
const res = await fetch(\`https://huggingface.co/api/models/\${repoId}\`);
const data = await res.json();

// data.safetensors
// data.usedStorage
// data.tags
// data.siblings`;

const codeBrowser = `const adapter = await navigator.gpu?.requestAdapter();
const gpuName = adapter?.info?.device;
const ramGB = navigator.deviceMemory;
const cores = navigator.hardwareConcurrency;`;

const codeVerdict = `estimate = combine(hfMetadata, browserHardware);

if (estimate.memoryUse < safeHeadroom) return "Runs great";
if (estimate.memoryUse < maxBudget) return "Tight fit";
return "Too heavy";`;
---

<Layout
  title="Why - Hugging Face compatibility estimates - CanIRun.ai"
  description="How CanIRun.ai detects your hardware, reads Hugging Face model metadata, and estimates whether a repo will run locally."
>
  <NavHeader />
  <main class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-12 sm:px-6">
    <header class="mb-10 text-center">
      <h1 class="font-pixel text-2xl tracking-tight text-accent sm:text-3xl">Why</h1>
      <p class="mt-2 text-base text-muted">
        How we detect your hardware, read Hugging Face metadata, and turn that into local run estimates.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="space-y-12">
      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-3 font-pixel text-base text-primary">How the new checker works</h2>
        <p class="text-base leading-relaxed text-secondary">
          The new flow starts from a Hugging Face model URL. We parse the repo id, fetch metadata from Hugging Face, estimate the model footprint, detect your hardware in the browser, and then compare both sides to produce a verdict.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-3 font-pixel text-base text-primary">1. Read the HF repo</h2>
        <p class="mb-3 text-base leading-relaxed text-secondary">
          We call the Hugging Face API and inspect whatever signals the repo exposes: tags, architecture, safetensors metadata, checkpoint filenames, used storage, and adapter hints.
        </p>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-md bg-surface p-3">
          <pre class="font-mono text-[13px] leading-relaxed text-secondary">{codeHF}</pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-3 font-pixel text-base text-primary">2. Detect your hardware</h2>
        <p class="mb-3 text-base leading-relaxed text-secondary">
          Hardware detection happens in the browser. We use browser APIs to gather GPU identity, RAM hints, and CPU details, then map those into memory and bandwidth estimates.
        </p>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-md bg-surface p-3">
          <pre class="font-mono text-[13px] leading-relaxed text-secondary">{codeBrowser}</pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-3 font-pixel text-base text-primary">3. Estimate memory and verdict</h2>
        <p class="mb-3 text-base leading-relaxed text-secondary">
          After we infer the likely weight format and model size, we estimate VRAM and RAM needs. Then we compare that to your detected machine and translate the result into a simple verdict.
        </p>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-md bg-surface p-3">
          <pre class="font-mono text-[13px] leading-relaxed text-secondary">{codeVerdict}</pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-3 font-pixel text-base text-primary">Why some repos are harder</h2>
        <p class="text-base leading-relaxed text-secondary">
          Not every Hugging Face repo is equally descriptive. Some repos expose exact safetensors parameter counts. Others only expose a PyTorch checkpoint, a TensorFlow SavedModel, or an adapter without the base weights. In those cases we fall back to file size and structural hints.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-3 font-pixel text-base text-primary">Why Hugging Face is now the center</h2>
        <p class="text-base leading-relaxed text-secondary">
          Hugging Face gives us one consistent place for models, metadata, files, adapters, and future artifacts. That makes it the best base for expanding this site beyond model checks into datasets, Spaces, and later comparison tools built around the HF ecosystem.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-3 font-pixel text-base text-primary">What stays local</h2>
        <p class="text-base leading-relaxed text-secondary">
          Your hardware detection stays in the browser. We only fetch Hugging Face repo metadata needed for the estimate. The verdict is an estimate, not a guarantee, because browser APIs and public repo metadata are both imperfect.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>

    <Footer />
  </main>
</Layout>
